etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales. From scientific Latin Enteropneusta, class name (C. GegenbaurGrundzüge der vergl. Anatomie 158 as Enteropneusti; from ancient Greek ἔντερον intestine + -πνευστος

definitions: Any of various worm-like hemichordates constituting the class Enteropneusta, having an acorn-shaped proboscis, a collar, and a long trunk, inhabiting U-shaped burrows in marine sediments; an acorn worm.

notes.text: A characteristic anatomical feature of enteropneusts is the presence of gill slits in the pharynx (the upper part of the digestive tract).

definitions: Of, relating to, or characteristic of an enteropneust or the class Enteropneusta.
